SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT THIS SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (this Agreement) is entered into as of December 20, 2024 (the Effective Date), by and among Roadrunner Solar SF LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (SF 1), Roadrunner BESS SF LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (SF 2), and each New CoTenant from time to time party hereto (and together with SF 1 and SF 2, the CoTenants and each separately as a CoTenant) and SF 2 in its capacity as the Manager on the Effective Date (the Initial Manager, and collectively with the CoTenants, the Parties, and each individually a Party). RECITALS: A. Roadrunner Solar LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Roadrunner PVCo) is developing an approximately 235 MWac/290 MWdc rated solar photovoltaic electricity generation and transmission facility on real property located in Cochise County, Arizona that will include photovoltaic modules, inverters and associated collection and interconnection lines and related facilities and improvements (collectively, the Roadrunner PV Project). B. Roadrunner Battery Storage LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Roadrunner BatteryCo) is developing an approximately 235 Mwac/940 MWh battery energy storage facility on real property adjacent to the Roadrunner PV Project also located in Cochise County, Arizona that will include battery storage facilities and associated collection and interconnection lines, related facilities and improvements (collectively, the Roadrunner BESS Project). C. One or more new project companies (including, without limitation, those set forth on Exhibit G) may from time to time develop, construct, own and operate other projects adjacent to or in the vicinity of the aforementioned projects and may desire to utilize the Shared Assets for the delivery of electricity subject to the conditions set forth herein (such new project companies and together with Roadrunner PVCo and Roadrunner BatteryCo are each hereinafter referred to as a Project Company, and the project and project site corresponding to each Project Company, each a Project and a Project Site, respectively). Each Project Company holds or shall hold its own individual real property rights (by option, lease, easement, right of way, in fee, or otherwise) to its respective Project Site. D. The ownership, development, construction, operation and maintenance of the Projects require the use of (i) certain real property more particularly described on Exhibit A-2 attached hereto (as amended or supplemented from time to time, the Shared Premises) and (ii) certain common infrastructure facilities supporting the construction, operation and maintenance of the Projects, including electrical transmission facilities, a substation, operations and maintenance facilities, laydown and staging areas for construction and other related facilities all as more particularly described in Exhibit C (collectively the Shared Facilities, and together with the Shared Premises, the Shared Assets). E. Each of the CoTenants owns an undivided interest in and to the Shared Facilities and real property rights to the Shared Premises as a tenant in common. Roadrunner BatteryCo directly owns 100% ownership interest in and to each CoTenant. F. Each of the Co-Tenants will enter into a Lease Agreement substantially in the form of Exhibit J (each, a Lease Agreement), respectively with each of Roadrunner PVCo and Roadrunner BatteryCo to provide the use of the Shared Facilities and the Shared Premises for the development, construction, operation and maintenance of the Applicable Project for such Person. G. Roadrunner PVCo and Roadrunner BatteryCo entered into (i) that certain Second Amended and Restated Standard Large Generator Interconnection Agreement (the Interconnection Agreement), dated as of June 27, 2024, with Arizona Electric Power Cooperative, Inc., a non-profit corporation organized and existing under the laws of the State of Arizona (Transmission Provider or Transmission Owner), for the purpose of securing interconnection rights for the Applicable Projects and (ii) that certain Large Generator Interconnection Agreement CoTenancy Agreement (the CoTenancy Agreement), dated as of the date hereof, with SF 2 in its capacity as the Manager under the CoTenancy Agreement, for the purpose of managing such parties respective rights and obligations under the Interconnection Agreement. H. The CoTenants wish to set forth herein their respective rights and obligations regarding the joint design, procurement, development, construction, installation, ownership, use, maintenance, repair, replacement of, and additions to, the Shared Facilities and the Shared Premises, taking into account requirements under the Lease Agreements, the Interconnection Agreement and the CoTenancy Agreement. I. The CoTenants also wish to contract with the Manager for the provision of certain limited services to be performed at the pleasure of the CoTenants, with respect to the Shared Facilities and the Shared Premises, and the Manager wishes to accept said engagement on the terms and conditions contained herein. AGREEMENT: NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants contained in this Agreement and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows: 1. DEFINITIONS AND INTERPRETATION 1.1 Definitions . Unless otherwise noted, capitalized terms not defined in the body of this Agreement have the following meanings. AAA has the meaning set forth in Section 15.1.1. Additional Shared Assets has the meaning set forth in Section 3.6. Additional Shared Facilities has the meaning set forth in Section 3.6. Additional Shared Premises has the meaning set forth in Section 3.6. Affiliate means, when used with respect to any Person, any other Person directly or indirectly controlling, controlled by, or under common control with such Person. For this definition, the terms controlling, controlled by or under common control mean the possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct or cause the direction of management or policies (whether through ownership of securities or any partnership or other ownership interest, by contract or otherwise) of a Person. After-Tax Basis means, with respect to any payment to be actually or constructively received by any Person (i) in the case such payment is compensation for Project Tax Benefits or an amount that would not have been taxable to the payee, the amount of such payment (the base payment) supplemented by a further payment (the additional payment) to that Person so that the sum of the base payment plus the additional payment, after deduction of the amount of all federal income taxes required to be paid by such Person in respect of the receipt or accrual of the base payment and the additional payment, calculating such federal income taxes using an assumed rate equal to the highest marginal rate, equals the amount required to be received and (ii) in the case such payment is compensation for an amount that would have been taxable to the payee, the base payment. Agreement has the meaning set forth in the preamble above, as amended and modified from time to time as permitted herein. Annual Shared Facilities Budget has the meaning set forth in Section 8.6. Applicable Agreement means (a) with respect to SF 1, the Lease Agreement between SF 1 and Roadrunner PVCo, dated as of the Effective Date, (b) with respect to SF 2, the Lease Agreement between SF 2 and Roadrunner BatteryCo, dated as of the Effective Date, and (c) with respect to a New CoTenant, the Lease Agreement between such New CoTenant and the Applicable Project Company for such New Co-Tenant. Applicable Construction Costs has the meaning set forth in Section 4.4. Applicable EPC Agreement means the engineering, procurement and construction agreement entered into for a Segment between the Constructing Party for such Segment and the applicable contractor. Applicable Project means (a) with respect to SF 1, the Roadrunner PV Project, (b) with respect to SF 2, the Roadrunner BESS Project, and (c) with respect to any New CoTenant, any Project owned and developed by the Applicable Project Company for such New CoTenant. Applicable Project Company means (a) with respect to SF 1, Roadrunner PVCo, (b) with respect to SF 2, Roadrunner BatteryCo, and (c) with respect to any New CoTenant, the Project Company that owns the Applicable Project for such New Co-Tenant. Applicable Project Site means, with respect to each CoTenant, the Project Site on which the Applicable Project for such CoTenant is located. Business Day means any day other than Saturday, Sunday or any other day when banks in New York City, New York are required or authorized to be closed. Casualty Event means an event that causes all or a portion of the Shared Facilities or the Shared Premises to be damaged, destroyed or rendered unfit or unavailable for normal use for any reason whatsoever. CoTenancy Agreement has the meaning set forth in Recital I. Co-Tenant and CoTenants have the respective meanings in the preamble to this Agreement. CoTenant Property has the meaning set forth in Section 8.16.1. Code means Internal Revenue Code of 1986 (as amended from time to time). Condemnation Event means any compulsory transfer or taking or transfer under threat of compulsory transfer or taking of all or a portion of the Shared Facilities or Shared Premises by any Governmental Authority or entity acting under power of eminent domain such that the Shared Facilities or Shared Premises are rendered unfit or unavailable for normal use. Confidential Information means, collectively and individually, all data, materials and information (including software, data, technology, know-how, trade secrets, processes, ideas, inventions (whether patentable or not), prototypes, schematics, design plans, drawings, pricing information, customer and service provider lists, business arrangements, business information, financial information, financial results, technical information, analyses, forecasts, compilations, studies, contracts, agreements, and planning or strategy information) provided by or on behalf of a Party or the Applicable Project Company for such Party (each Party and Applicable Project Company in such capacity, a Disclosing Party) to any other Party or the Applicable Project Company for such other Party (each Party and Applicable Project Company in such capacity, a Receiving Party) or the Receiving Partys Representatives, or to which the Receiving Party or the Receiving Partys Representatives are given access by or on behalf of the Disclosing Party, whether verbally or in written or electronic form, related to the Disclosing Party, any Applicable Project Company, any Applicable Project, the Shared Facilities, the Shared Premises or the Parties in connection with this Agreement before, on, or after the Effective Date. Notwithstanding the foregoing, Confidential Information under this Agreement does not include any information that: (a) is now publicly available, or that later becomes publicly available through no action by the Receiving Party or the Receiving Partys Representatives in violation of this Agreement; (b) is already in the possession of the Receiving Party or the Receiving Partys Representatives and is not, to the Receiving Partys knowledge, subject to a confidentiality obligation at the time of the informations disclosure under this Agreement; (c) is lawfully received from any source other than the Disclosing Party or the Disclosing Partys Representatives under circumstances not involving, to the Receiving Partys knowledge, a breach of any fiduciary or confidentiality obligation; or (d) is independently developed by or for the Receiving Party or the Receiving Partys Representatives without reference to, or the use of, any portion of the Confidential Information. Confidential Information shall also include the terms and conditions of this Agreement. Constructing Party(ies) has the meaning set forth in Section 4.3. Construction Costs has the meaning set forth in Section 4.3. Default Rate means a rate per annum equal to the lesser of (a) a varying rate per annum equal to the sum of (i) the prime rate as defined and published in The Wall Street Journal, with adjustments in that varying rate to be made on the same date as any change in that rate is so published, plus (ii) two percent (2%) per annum and (b) the maximum rate permitted by Law. Demand has the meaning set forth in Section 15.1.3. Disclosing Party has the meaning set forth in the definition of Confidential Information. Dispute means any controversy, claim or dispute between or among the Parties that arises out of or in connection with this Agreement or the construction, interpretation, performance, breach, termination, enforceability or validity of this Agreement, whether the same is based on rights, privileges or interests recognized by or based upon statute, contract, agreement (whether written or oral), tort, common law or other Law. Effective Date has the meaning set forth in the preamble. Emergency shall mean any occurrence, in the reasonable judgment of the Manager or a CoTenant, that (i) may arise that requires immediate action in order to prevent or mitigate serious actual or potential hazard to the safety of persons or property, or (ii) may result in material interference with the safe, economical, reliable, or environmentally sound operation of the Shared Facilities, the Shared Premises or any Applicable Project, or (iii) would or could cause a violation of any applicable Law or Governmental Approval or any directive by a Governmental Authority or operating commitment made by a Party to Transmission Provider. Environmental Laws means all Laws, whenever enacted or in effect concerning pollution, protection of human health, safety or the environment or preservation or reclamation of natural resources (including endangered or threatened species), or relating to the use, storage, disposal, generation and transportation of Hazardous Substances or imposing liability for injury to human health, property or the environment. Event of Default has the meaning set forth in Section 14.1. EWG means an exempt wholesale generator, as such term is defined in Section 1262(6) of the Public Utility Holding Company Act of 2005 and the FERCs regulations at 18 C.F.R. Pt. 366.1. FERC means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or its successor agency. FERC Filing has the meaning set forth in Section 3.8. Financing Party means, with respect to a CoTenant, any Person providing direct or indirect debt or equity financing, refinancing or extending credit (including any financing lease) to such CoTenant or the Applicable Project Company for such CoTenant. For the purposes of this Agreement, with respect to a CoTenant, any counterparty to such CoTenant or the Applicable Project Company for such CoTenant in a swap, option collar or cap involving, or settled by reference to, one (1) or more commodities (including power and transmission) or meteorological conditions (whether financial or physical), in each case, in connection with the purchase, installation or operation of the applicable solar photovoltaic panels or Applicable Project, shall be a Financing Party hereunder. Force Majeure means acts of God or any other casualty or occurrence, condition, event or circumstance of any kind or nature not reasonably within the affected Partys or its Applicable Project Companys control and which could not have been avoided by reasonable measures by the affected Party or its Applicable Project Company, including strikes, slow-downs or labor difficulties, fires, flood, earthquakes, explosions, natural disasters, or other hazards, acts of public enemies, riots, civil commotions, insurrection, war, or actions or failures to act by a Governmental Authority. Force Majeure expressly does not include: any delay in performing or failure of performance of any contractual provision by a Party or its Applicable Project Company (except to the extent caused by a Force Majeure event); late delivery or breakage of equipment or materials (except to the extent caused by a Force Majeure event); or economic hardship. GAAP means United States generally accepted accounting principles as in effect from time to time, applied on a consistent basis. GIF means Interconnection Customers Interconnection Facilities as defined in the Interconnection Agreement, to the extent it applies to any Applicable Project. Governmental Approval means any permit, license, certificate, concession, approval, consent, ratification, permission, clearance, confirmation, exemption, waiver, franchise, certification, designation, rating, registration, variance, qualification, accreditation or authorization issued, granted, given or otherwise made available by or under the authority of any Governmental Authority or pursuant to any Law. Governmental Authority means any court, tribunal, authority, agency, commission, official or other instrumentality, including regulatory authorities and bodies, of the United States or any state, county, city, school district, hospital district, or other political subdivision, any quasi-governmental regulatory authority, such as NERC, or NERCs regional reliability entities acting under delegated authority, as well as any arbitrator or any judicial or quasi-judicial tribunal of competent jurisdiction. Hazardous Substances means: (a) any hazardous materials, hazardous wastes, hazardous substances, toxic wastes, solid wastes, and toxic substances as those or similar terms are defined under any Environmental Laws; (b) any asbestos or asbestos containing material; (c) polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs), or PCB containing materials or fluids; (d) radon; (e) any petroleum, petroleum hydrocarbons, petroleum products, crude oil and any fractions or derivatives thereof; and (f) any other hazardous, radioactive, toxic or noxious substance, material, pollutant, or contaminant that, whether by its nature, its use, or the consequences of exposure to it, is subject to regulation or could give rise to liability under any Environmental Laws. Indemnified Parties has the meaning set forth in Section 11.1. Initial Manager has the meaning set forth in the preamble above. Interconnection Agreement has the meaning set forth in Recital I. Interest Rate means the lesser of (i) Prime Rate plus 400 basis points, or (ii) the maximum rate allowed by law. ITCs means the investment tax credits with respect to a Project under Sections 48 or 48E of the Code. Land Matters means any and all covenants, conditions, restrictions, and other encumbrances, including leases and subleases, affecting the applicable real property and binding upon the owner, tenant, licensee, easement holder, or any other user or occupant of that real property. Laws means any applicable constitutional provisions, statutes, acts, codes, laws, rules, regulations, ordinances, protocols, standards, orders, decrees, rulings, judgments or decisions of a Governmental Authority or arbitral body. Lease Agreement has the meaning set forth in Recital H. Liabilities means any and all claims, actions, debts, losses, liabilities, damages, expenses, awards, judgments, settlement payments, fines, penalties (including any penalties imposed or damages payable to a power purchaser, Transmission Provider or any Governmental Authority), costs, royalties, assessments (tax or otherwise), deficiencies or obligations, whether civil or criminal, including those arising out of any investigation, action, claim, proceeding, settlement, compromise, judgment or award, by any Person, of any nature, including for personal injury, death or damage to real property and tangible personal property of or to any Party or any third party, whether known or unknown, absolute, accrued, contingent or otherwise and whether due or to become due, and whether or not resulting from third party claims, and any out-of-pocket costs and expenses (including court costs and fees, reasonable legal counsels, accountants, or other fees and expenses) incurred in defending against or investigating any of the same. Liens means all mortgages, deeds of trust, liens, debentures, security interests, pledges, conditional sale contracts, proceedings, judgment liens, orders, rights of first refusal, charges and other encumbrances or restrictions of any kind, whether recorded or unrecorded. Loss Event means a Casualty Event or a Condemnation Event. Major Decisions means: (a) any sale, lease or other voluntary disposition of all or any part of the Shared Assets, other than a Transfer in accordance with the requirements of Section 17.1; (b) any encumbrance or grant of any Lien on all or any part of the Shared Assets, other than any Permitted Liens; (c) any action that would adversely change or impact the regulatory status of any CoTenant, any Applicable Project Company or the Shared Assets; (d) any capital expenditures related to the Shared Facilities, that are individually or in the aggregate in excess of 110% of the amount budgeted therefor in the Annual Shared Facilities Budget, except during the continuation of an Emergency as necessary to address the impacts thereof; (e) any action that would materially and adversely impact any CoTenants interest in the Shared Assets; (f) any action that would materially and adversely impact any rights or responsibilities under the Interconnection Agreement (other than the rights of the Transmission Provider thereunder); or (g) the removal of the Manager pursuant to Section 7.4. Manager means the Person from time to time appointed as the Manager pursuant to Section 7.1, which as of the Effective Date is the Initial Manager. Manager Indemnified Parties has the meaning set forth in Section 11.2. Manager Representative has the meaning set forth in Section 8.13. Managers Fee means a fee of $25,000.00 per year (or a pro-rated portion thereof for any partial year during which the Manager provides services) payable quarterly in advance to the Manager for its services hereunder, subject to an increase of 2% per year. Maximum Capacity has the meaning set forth in Section 5.2.1. MBR Authority has the meaning set forth in Section 6.7.1. Minimum Experience Requirements means a Person (a) is a CoTenant or (b) has or contracts with an entity that has no less than three (3) years in the electric generation and storage industry managing interconnection facilities similar in size and complexity to the Shared Facilities. NERC means the North American Electric Reliability Corporation and any successor entity serving as the Electric Reliability Organization as certified by FERC. New CoTenant means a Person that becomes a CoTenant to this Agreement pursuant to Section 6.16. New York Courts has the meaning set forth in Section 15.1.6. Parties and Party have the respective meanings set forth in the preamble above. PCBs has the meaning set forth in the definition of Hazardous Substances. Percentage Interest means the percentage as set forth on Exhibit B attached hereto with respect to each CoTenant, as the same may be updated from time to time following the addition of any New CoTenant as a party to this Agreement pursuant to Section 6.16. Permitted Liens means any of the following, but in each case only to the extent placed upon any of the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Premises: (a) Liens for taxes that (i) are not yet delinquent or (ii) are being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings and for which adequate reserves have been established in accordance with GAAP, so long as any such proceeding does not involve any risk greater than a de minimis risk of the sale, forfeiture or loss of any part of the Shared Assets; (b) Liens in favor of carriers, warehousemen, mechanics, materialmen, repairmen or other like Liens that (i) arise in the ordinary course of business of and for amounts that are not yet due or (ii) are being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings and for which adequate reserves have been established in accordance with GAAP, so long as any such proceeding does not involve any risk greater than a de minimis risk of the sale, forfeiture or loss of any part of the Shared Assets; (c) Liens in favor of Financing Parties permitted pursuant to Section 17.2.1; (d) Liens arising out of judgments or awards so long as enforcement has been stayed and for the payment of which adequate reserves in accordance with GAAP, bonds or other security have been provided or are fully covered by insurance; (e) minor defects, easements, licenses, rights-of-way, restrictions and other similar encumbrances incurred in the ordinary course of business, and encumbrances consisting of the zoning restrictions, licenses, restrictions on the use of property or minor imperfections in title, which do not materially impair the property affected thereby for the purpose for which title was acquired or materially interfere with the operation of the applicable Project; or (f) Liens incurred in the ordinary course of business in connection with surety and appeal bonds, performance bonds, workers compensation, unemployment insurance, social security, other governmental rules and other obligations of a like nature to the foregoing that do not in the aggregate materially impair the use of the property or assets of the applicable CoTenant or the value of such property or assets for the purposes of such business. Person means any individual, partnership, joint stock company, corporation, limited liability company, trust, unincorporated association or joint venture, any Governmental Authority, or any other entity. Prudent Industry Practices does not necessarily mean the best practice, method, or standard of care, skill, safety and diligence in all cases, but is instead intended to encompass a range of acceptable practices, methods, and standards. PTCs means the production tax credits with respect to a Project under Sections 45 or 45Y of the Code. Receiving Party has the meaning set forth in the definition of Confidential Information. Reimbursable Segments has the meaning set forth in Section 4.3. Subject to the subordination provisions of Section 5.2 below, the total net output of the Applicable Project Company for a CoTenant may exceed such CoTenants Undivided Interest (determined as a percentage of the aggregate capacity under the Interconnection Agreement); provided, that in no event shall the net output of the Applicable Project Company for a CoTenant exceed such CoTenants Maximum Capacity. The net output of each Party shall be subject to allocation by the Transmission Provider. 5.2 Maximum Capacity of Applicable Projects. 5.2.1 The maximum capacity (Maximum Capacity) shall mean, with respect to any Applicable Project, the maximum net capacity of such Applicable Project as measured at the point of interconnection, in MW, and set forth in Exhibit D, which Maximum Capacity may be changed only in accordance with this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement, and the CoTenancy Agreement. Each CoTenant shall cause its Applicable Project Company to construct its Applicable Project with a net generation or storage capacity, as applicable, of up to, but not in excess of, the Maximum Capacity of such Applicable Project as set forth on Exhibit D. 5.2.2 The priority applicable to each Co-Tenant and Project Companys ability to use its Undivided Interest in the Shared Facilities is set forth in Exhibit D. No Co-Tenant or Project Company may use its Undivided Interest or Maximum Capacity in the Shared Facilities in a manner that impinges upon, reduces, impairs, or otherwise limits the ability of another Co-Tenant or Project Company to use its Undivided Interest or Maximum Capacity as set forth in Exhibit D. 5.2.3 No New CoTenant will be afforded a Maximum Capacity if such New CoTenants allocated Maximum Capacity will impinge upon, reduce, impair, or otherwise limit the Maximum Capacity of any of the Project Companies, or the rights of SF 1 or SF 2, to use the Shared Facilities to the full extent of each such CoTenants respective Maximum Capacity except as otherwise set forth herein. 5.2.4 For the avoidance of doubt, subject to the subordination of rights set forth above, each CoTenants Undivided Interest in this Agreement and the Shared Facilities shall convey Segment Interests sufficient to convey the full Maximum Capacity of such CoTenants Applicable Project to and from the point of interconnection. 5.3 Shared Facilities Representatives . On or promptly following the Commercial Operation Date (as defined in the Interconnection Agreement) of the Applicable Project with respect to a CoTenant, such CoTenant shall, by written notice to the other CoTenants and the Manager, designate an individual (the Shared Facilities Representative), who will have authority to bind the CoTenant in all matters concerning this Agreement (other than to amend or terminate this Agreement) and to communicate with the other CoTenants and the Manager, if applicable, regarding issues relating to this Agreement, including operational and maintenance issues. Each CoTenant may change its Shared Facilities Representative at any time and from time to time by prior written notice to the other CoTenants and the Manager. 5.4 Liens . No CoTenant shall create, permit or suffer to exist by, through or under such CoTenant or its Representatives, and hereby waives for itself and its Representatives, any Liens on the interests in the Shared Assets, the Undivided Interests, or Project Specific Assets held by the other CoTenants or their respective Applicable Project Companies. No CoTenant shall create, permit or suffer to exist by, through or under such CoTenant or its Representatives any Liens on the Shared Assets, the Undivided Interests, or Project Specific Assets with respect to such CoTenant or its respective Applicable Project Company, in each case, other than Permitted Liens. Each CoTenant shall, as to any Lien the imposition of which is its responsibility, take prompt steps to discharge any Lien (other than a Permitted Lien) filed against any portion of the Shared Assets, the Undivided Interest or Project Specific Assets with respect to the other CoTenants or their respective Applicable Project Companies. If any CoTenant responsible for the imposition of a Lien (other than a Permitted Lien) fails to discharge promptly any such Lien, the other CoTenants, in addition to any other rights it may have at law or equity for a breach of this Agreement, shall have the right to notify the responsible CoTenant in writing and to take any reasonable action to satisfy, defend, settle or otherwise remove the Lien at the responsible CoTenants expense. 6. OBLIGATIONS AND CERTAIN RIGHTS OF THE COTENANTS 6.1 Standards of Performance . Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement to the contrary, each CoTenant will cause the Applicable Project Company for such CoTenant to design, procure, install, operate and/or maintain, or cause to be designed, procured, constructed, installed, operated and maintained, its Applicable Project (including any Project Specific Assets for such Applicable Project Company), use the Shared Facilities and the Shared Premises and perform its obligations under this Agreement, in each case in all material respects, in accordance with (a) all applicable Laws, (b) Prudent Industry Practices, (c) the terms of the Interconnection Agreement, the CoTenancy Agreement, the Shared Premises Agreements, and the Applicable Agreement for such CoTenant, (d) the Tariff, and (e) any and all Governmental Approvals. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, each CoTenant will cause the Applicable Project Company for such CoTenant to design, procure, install, operate and/or maintain, or cause to be designed, procured, installed, operated and maintained, its Applicable Project so that it is capable of operating in compliance with the Tariff (including with respect to the provision of mandatory ancillary services) when any other Applicable Project is disconnected from the Shared Facilities. Except as provided herein, no CoTenant will permit the Applicable Project Company for such CoTenant to take any action, omit to take any action or fail to perform any obligation under this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement, the CoTenancy Agreement, the Shared Premises Agreements, any Governmental Approvals or the Applicable Agreement for such CoTenant that materially and adversely affects any other CoTenant or its Applicable Project or gives rise to a Liability affecting such other CoTenant or its Applicable Project, the Shared Facilities or the Shared Premises, including any action, omission or failure to perform an obligation that results in damage to, disconnection of, imposes costs on, or results in an outage of such other CoTenants Applicable Project or termination of the Interconnection Agreement, unless required to do so by applicable Law. 6.2 Taxes . Unless otherwise directed by the CoTenants, the Manager shall pay all taxes levied against the Shared Assets before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty will become due or be imposed for their non-payment, except that the Manager may withhold payment of any tax if the Manager is contesting the payment of such tax in good faith by appropriate proceedings and such proceedings do not involve any danger of the sale, forfeiture or loss of any part of the Shared Assets, including the posting of any bond that is required by applicable Law to avoid such sale, forfeiture or loss while the payment of such tax is being contested and notifies all of the CoTenants thereof in writing at least thirty (30) days before such payment is due or paid. All such taxes paid by the Manager (including the cost of posting any bond) shall be treated as Shared Expenses and invoiced to the CoTenants in accordance with Section 4.2. Each CoTenant acknowledges that it shall be liable for its own taxes with respect to the Undivided Interest or Shared Premises owned by such CoTenant. If any CoTenant is assessed taxes or otherwise becomes liable for taxes with respect to the Undivided Interest or Shared Premises owned by another CoTenant, such CoTenant that owns such Undivided Interest or Shared Premises shall provide the funds necessary to pay such taxes to the CoTenant against whom the taxes are assessed or whom otherwise becomes liable for such taxes, or, if such CoTenant pays such taxes in advance of receipt of such payment, reimburse such CoTenant for any such taxes so paid. 6.3 Environmental Compliance . Each CoTenant shall cause the Applicable Project Company for such CoTenant to, with respect to its Applicable Project (including its Project Specific Assets and the Applicable Project Site upon which its Applicable Project is installed), be responsible for and have exclusive control over all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by (a) any Governmental Authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters, or (b) any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to such Applicable Project Companys use, operation or ownership of its Applicable Project (including its Project Specific Assets and the Applicable Project Site). The Manager shall, with respect to the Shared Assets, subject to the oversight and direction of the CoTenants, oversee all investigations, studies, clean-up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any Governmental Authority or by any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to the Shared Premises or the CoTenants or the Applicable Project Companies use, operation or ownership of the Shared Assets. The Manager shall keep the CoTenants fully apprised as to the above matters and shall consult with all of them prior to taking any action involving any Governmental Authority or risk of incurring any Liability. The provisions of this Section 6.3 shall not be construed to modify the responsibilities of individual Parties arising under Section 4.1 or Section 11.1. 6.4 Interconnection . Except to the extent otherwise provided in the CoTenancy Agreement, each Applicable Project Company shall be solely responsible for securing for its own benefit, and for maintaining, such rights as are necessary to interconnect its Applicable Project with the transmission system in accordance with the Interconnection Agreement. Any CoTenant or any Applicable Project Company may take such actions as may be necessary to comply with any order or instruction received from Transmission Provider or any other balancing authority, and nothing herein shall require any CoTenant or any Applicable Project Company to violate, contest, or appeal the requirements of any such order. This Agreement does not grant any rights to interconnection service or other rights under any interconnection agreement to any Person that is not a party to such interconnection agreement. 6.5 Voting or Approval Rights . Unless specifically provided in this Agreement, each CoTenant shall have an approval right over any matter requiring or needing a vote or approval of the CoTenants that relates to or affects a Segment for which such CoTenant has a Segment Interest. Unless otherwise specified herein, the written approval of the Required Parties, acting reasonably, shall be required for any approval to be provided hereunder; provided, however, that during the occurrence and continuance of an Event of Default by a CoTenant, the voting and approval rights of such CoTenant shall be suspended. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, any Major Decision shall require the unanimous approval of the non-defaulting CoTenants. 6.6 Relationship of the Parties . The rights, duties, obligations and liabilities of the Parties under this Agreement will be individual and several, and not joint or collective, and no Party shall be responsible for the default of any other Party under this Agreement. It is not the intention of the Parties to create, nor will this Agreement be deemed to create, any partnership, agency, joint venture or trust, or to authorize any Party (other than the Manager on behalf of the CoTenants, and then only as and to the extent expressly provided in this Agreement) to act as an agent, servant or employee for any other Party. Except as expressly provided herein, no Party is authorized to act as agent for, to act on behalf of, or to do any act that will bind any other party or to incur any obligations with respect to the Shared Premises or Shared Facilities. The employees, agents, and subcontractors of the Parties, in performing the obligations of each respective Party under this Agreement, shall not be deemed to be the agents or employees or subcontractors of any other Party. Each Party will remain solely responsible for the actions of its own employees, members, managers, officers, contractors, subcontractors, agents, and representatives. 6.7 Regulatory Status . 6.7.1 Each CoTenant shall provide written notice to the other CoTenants and the Manager no later than sixty (60) days prior to the initial anticipated production, sale, receipt or delivery of any electric energy, capacity or ancillary services from the Applicable Project for such CoTenant, including test energy. Each CoTenant shall, prior to any production, sale, receipt or delivery of energy, capacity or ancillary services from the Applicable Project for such CoTenant (including test energy), obtain and thereafter maintain (a) status as an EWG for so long as it is a party to this Agreement or has any interest in the Shared Facilities, and (b) market-based rate authority from FERC (MBR Authority) pursuant to the Federal Power Act and 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, each as amended. No CoTenant shall permit the Applicable Project Company for such CoTenant to take, and such CoTenant shall ensure that none of such Applicable Project Companys Affiliates take, any action that could adversely impact any other CoTenants or its Applicable Project Companys ability to qualify as an EWG, or the status of another CoTenant or its Applicable Project Company that has already self-certified or obtained FERC certification as a qualifying small power production facility under Section 3(17)(C) of the Federal Power Act and FERCs regulations, and holds such status under 18 C.F.R. Part 292, or that could prevent or impede another CoTenants or its Applicable Project Companys ability to obtain and maintain MBR Authority. 6.7.2 If any Co-Tenant whose Applicable Project is a generation facility receives a communication from FERC that such Co-Tenants status as an EWG has been revoked or is subject to an investigation or review that may result in revocation pursuant to 18 C.F.R. § 366.7(d)(2) or other applicable FERC regulation as a result of the actions of another Co-Tenant, including the consumption or use of electric energy such other Co-Tenants Applicable Project, the Co-Tenants shall promptly attempt to negotiate in good faith a revision to this Agreement that resolves the issue with respect to EWG status while otherwise maintaining the intent of this Agreement to the greatest extent possible, and shall file such amended Agreement with FERC. In the event that agreement cannot be reached within sixty (60) days, or immediately if FERC notifies the affected Co-Tenant of a violation of PUHCA, the affected Co-Tenant, notwithstanding anything to the contrary in this Agreement, shall have the right to terminate this Agreement with immediate effect. Upon termination, the Manager shall act in accordance with Section 7.6. 6.7.3 It is the Parties intent that no CoTenant or Applicable Project Company will, solely as the result of the execution and delivery of this Agreement and the consummation of the transactions contemplated by this Agreement, become subject to, or not exempt from, regulation as a public utility by the State PRC. 6.7.4 No CoTenant shall (and each CoTenant shall cause the Applicable Project Company for such CoTenant not to) use the Shared Facilities in a manner that would cause any CoTenant or any Applicable Project Company to be subject to, or not exempt from, regulation by the State PRC as a public utility or that would or could reasonably be expected to cause the Manager, or any CoTenant or Applicable Project Company, to be in violation of the Tariff or of any FERC regulation. 6.7.5 Subject to Section 5.1, each CoTenant whose Applicable Project is a generation facility shall use the Shared Assets only for the purpose of transmitting wholesale electricity generated from such Applicable Project (or to carry backfeed power to such Applicable Project) in a manner consistent with the requirements of the Interconnection Agreement and the CoTenancy Agreement. Subject to Section 5.1, no CoTenant shall (and each CoTenant shall cause the Applicable Project Company for such CoTenant not to) use the Shared Facilities to receive or transmit an amount of electrical energy greater than that CoTenants Undivided Interest in the Shared Facilities (determined as a percentage of the aggregate capacity under the Interconnection Agreement). Each CoTenant and the Applicable Project Company therefor shall avoid taking any action which would cause the Shared Facilities to be subject to, or not eligible for waiver of, any open access requirements, to the extent permitted pursuant to the applicable regulations of the FERC and the Interconnection Agreement. Subject to Section 5.1, the CoTenants acknowledge and agree that each CoTenant will, and will cause its Applicable Project Company to, use no more than its Undivided Interest (determined as a percentage of the aggregate capacity under the Interconnection Agreement) in the Shared Facilities to receive or transmit electrical energy from its Applicable Project and that (a) no CoTenant or Applicable Project Company will provide any interconnection or transmission services to the other CoTenants or Applicable Project Companies under this Agreement, except to the extent required pursuant to an applicable regulation or order of the FERC, (b) no CoTenant or Applicable Project Company will pay a fee or make any other payment to the other CoTenants or Applicable Project Companies for the transmission of any other CoTenants or Applicable Project Companys electricity, and (c) no CoTenant or Applicable Project Company shall have any obligation under this Agreement to the other CoTenants or Applicable Project Companies to provide any interconnection or transmission service, except to the extent required pursuant to an applicable regulation or order of the FERC. 6.8 No Dedication of Property; No Public Access . Each Party agrees that entering into this Agreement, performing its obligations hereunder, or exercising its rights hereunder, either in whole or part, is not intended to be, and shall in no way be construed as or deemed to be a dedication to public or quasi-public use or purpose of any of the Project Specific Assets of the Party, the Project Specific Assets of another Party, any Shared Assets, or any portion of the foregoing. The CoTenants undertake to cooperate in enforcing such requirement for limiting physical access to the Shared Assets, including permitting the Manager to establish and enforce procedures and protocol for security, safety, and protection of the Shared Assets. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Parties shall comply with requirements set forth in any Governmental Approvals. 6.9 Crossing and Co-Location Rights . Each CoTenant and its Applicable Project Company hereunder shall be permitted to cross, encroach and overhang upon the Shared Premises with its Project Specific Assets solely to the extent necessary to develop, construct, operate and/or maintain its Applicable Project; provided that any such crossings, encroachments or overhang shall be subject to the noninterference protections of Section 3.5 above and are consistent with the Shared Premises Agreements, Land Matters related to the Shared Premises and the Project Sites and applicable Governmental Approvals. In particular, any CoTenants or its Applicable Project Companys exercise of rights under this Section 6.9 shall only be permitted in accordance with the Standard of Performance, and shall not interfere with or endanger the construction, operation, or maintenance of the Shared Assets, or any other CoTenants Project Specific Assets. In the event of a conflict in the location or operation of the Shared Facilities and any Project Specific Assets, the Shared Facilities shall take priority over the Project Specific Assets. 6.10 Cooperation in Financing . The Parties acknowledge that a CoTenant or its Applicable Project Company may finance all or part of its costs in connection with the transactions contemplated by this Agreement. In the event that a CoTenant or its Applicable Project Company enters into such financing, the Parties acknowledge and agree that certain aspects of the transactions contemplated hereby may need to be modified in certain respects to accommodate the reasonable requirements of any Financing Party with respect to such financing. Upon reasonable request of a Party, the other Party shall cooperate (and cause its Applicable Project Company to cooperate) in good faith to assist with the financing or refinancing of such requesting Partys Applicable Project, including the execution of estoppels, consents for the benefit of the Financing Parties and other similar agreements as may be reasonably requested by the requesting Party and its Financing Parties and the making of any filings required by such requesting Party for regulatory compliance or obtaining Governmental Approvals, and in connection with the operation and maintenance of such requesting Partys Applicable Project. The requesting CoTenant will be responsible for the documented attorneys fees and other out-of-pocket costs incurred by the other Parties or their respective Applicable Project Companies in providing such cooperation and efforts under this Section 6.10. 6.11 CoTenants Responsibilities to Manager . Each CoTenant shall do all of the following: (a) with the exception of information and data the Manager is required to record and collect hereunder, provide the Manager with all material information, including information related to Governmental Approvals, agreements, data and documents for the Shared Assets that is reasonably required for Manager to perform its obligations under this Agreement, including, but not limited to, any drawings, equipment identities, settings, etc., as required to support NERC compliance for the Shared Facilities; (b) promptly examine all material documents submitted by Manager and render any necessary decisions pertaining thereto; (c) promptly make all decisions required under this Agreement or any other agreement that the Manager may be requested to administer hereunder and respond to all reasonable requests from Manager for approval made hereunder; (d) promptly execute and deliver such evidence of Managers authority hereunder as may be reasonably required by third parties; (e) except where the same are being disputed in good faith, promptly make all payments and incur all expenditures required in connection with the Shared Assets in accordance with this Agreement; and (f) promptly provide the Manager with any communications received by the CoTenant or its Applicable Project Company from Transmission Provider or any Governmental Authority that are addressed to the Manager or that are sent to the CoTenant or its Applicable Project Company instead of the Manager by mistake of any such Person. 6.12 Outage, Curtailment or Disconnection . To the extent any Applicable Project Companys operating Applicable Project is disconnected, incurs any downtime, is curtailed or experiences an unscheduled outage, or has the Interconnection Agreement terminated, in each case resulting in a loss of production and revenue (including Revenue Losses) to such Applicable Project, and the loss arises from another CoTenants or Applicable Project Companys actions or inactions that were not in all respects required and compulsory under one or more applicable Laws, then, in any such case, without limiting a Partys indemnification obligations under Article 11, the responsible CoTenant shall reimburse the affected CoTenant (on an After-Tax Basis) for such Revenue Losses within thirty (30) days after calculation by an independent engineer, mutually appointed by the CoTenants, of the amount of the Revenue Losses. The CoTenant requesting reimbursement shall provide supporting documentation to the other CoTenant and the independent engineer, including, at a minimum if the Applicable Project is a generating facility, for the period of disconnection, downtime, curtailment or outage, as applicable, recorded solar and meteorological data from the affected Applicable Project and a calculation of the quantity of energy that would have been produced by the Applicable Project and delivered to the interconnection point (but was not produced and delivered) using the best available data or interpolated data, including solar availability, power curves, the number of operational solar panels, station service, transmission line losses, meteorological conditions or physical limitations. The affected CoTenants shall cooperate in appointing an independent engineer that is not affiliated with any CoTenant or any Applicable Project Company and is mutually acceptable to each CoTenant, in its reasonable discretion, to be responsible for calculating Revenue Losses. If the CoTenants do not mutually agree upon an independent engineer within thirty (30) days after the occurrence of any event described in the first sentence of this Section 6.12, then the Manager shall appoint an independent engineer that is not affiliated with any CoTenant. 6.13 Allocation of Output, Line Losses and Capacity Reductions; Scheduling . (a) Each CoTenant anticipates that the Applicable Projects will use a single settlement meter at the common point of interconnection with Transmission Providers transmission system (the Settlement Meter). Following the date that at least two Applicable Project Companies have commenced operations, output and consumption measured at the Settlement Meter, over any relevant time period, shall be allocated between or among the Applicable Project Companies by Transmission Provider in its settlement calculations, based on electricity metered by the revenue quality meters in the switchyard of each Applicable Project over such time period, in accordance with the Tariff. (b) Subject to the provisions of Section 6.12, any interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power through the Shared Facilities, or to the common point of interconnection designated in the Interconnection Agreement, in each case caused by the action or inaction of one CoTenant or its Applicable Project Company, shall be allocated as follows: first, and to the fullest extent possible, to the CoTenant and its Applicable Project Company that caused such interruption, reduction, or curtailment; second, to each CoTenant and its Applicable Project Company that is delivering or importing energy, as applicable, in excess of such CoTenants Maximum Capacity (if any) shall reduce deliveries or imports, as applicable, down to such CoTenants Maximum Capacity; provided, that, if the aggregate Maximum Capacity then utilized by SF 1 and SF 2 exceeds 235 MW, SF 2 shall reduce deliveries or imports, as applicable to cause the aggregate Maximum Capacity then utilized by SF 1 and SF 2 to 235 MW before SF 1 is called upon to reduce deliveries or imports; third, to each New CoTenant and their respective Applicable Project Companies in proportion to their respective Maximum Capacity, if any; fourth, to SF 2 and Roadrunner BatteryCo in proportion to its respective Maximum Capacity; and fifth, to the other CoTenants and their respective Applicable Project Companies in proportion to their respective Maximum Capacity. The CoTenant causing such interruption, reduction or curtailment shall compensate the other CoTenants (on an After-Tax Basis) for the Revenue Losses as a result, except where such interruption, reduction or curtailment was in all respects required and compulsory under one or more applicable Laws. Any other interruption, reduction in deliveries, or other curtailment of electrical power through the Shared Facilities, or to the point of interconnection designated in the Interconnection Agreement, that in each case is not caused by the action or inaction of any CoTenant or its Applicable Project Company, and which shall include but not be limited to curtailment required by Transmission Owner, Transmission Provider, other balancing authority, or a Governmental Authority, shall be allocated as follows: first, to each CoTenant and its Applicable Project Company that is delivering or importing energy, as applicable, in excess of such CoTenants Maximum Capacity (if any) shall reduce deliveries or imports, as applicable, down to such CoTenants Maximum Capacity; provided, that, if the aggregate Maximum Capacity then utilized by SF 1 and SF 2 exceeds 235 MW, SF 2 shall reduce deliveries or imports, as applicable to cause the aggregate Maximum Capacity then utilized by SF 1 and SF 2 to 235 MW before SF 1 is called upon to reduce deliveries or imports; second, to each New CoTenant and their respective Applicable Project Companies in proportion to their respective Maximum Capacity, if any; third, to SF 2 and Roadrunner BatteryCo in proportion to its respective Maximum Capacity; and fourth, to the other CoTenants and their respective Applicable Project Companies in proportion to their respective Maximum Capacity to the extent such CoTenants Applicable Project Companys facilities were in operation or were scheduled to receive or deliver electrical power for the period of such interruption, reduction in deliveries, or other curtailment of electrical power through the Shared Facilities. 6.14 Withdrawal of a CoTenant . 6.14.1 At its election in its sole discretion, a CoTenant may relinquish its Undivided Interest and cease to be a CoTenant by delivery of a written notice (a Withdrawal Notice) to the other CoTenant(s) and the Manager in which such CoTenant certifies, as of the date specified in the Withdrawal Notice (the later of (i) such date specified in the Withdrawal Notice and (ii) the date on which the Withdrawal Costs, as defined herein, if applicable are paid in full, a Withdrawal Date) that it has obtained all Governmental Approvals required by applicable Law, in each case at the sole cost and expense of the withdrawing CoTenant, in connection with the Transfer of its Undivided Interest to the other CoTenant(s) as contemplated in Section 6.14.2. A CoTenant shall provide at least thirty (30) days advance written notice to the other CoTenant(s) and the Manager of its intention to no longer be a CoTenant. On the Withdrawal Date, upon and subject to the terms, conditions, restrictions and reservations set forth in this Agreement, any such withdrawing CoTenant shall contemporaneously execute all instruments of transfer as may be necessary or appropriate to effect the conveyance of such withdrawing CoTenants Undivided Interest and assignment of all of its rights under this Agreement to, and which are reasonably satisfactory to, the remaining CoTenant(s). In the event the Applicable Project Company for a CoTenant desires to decommission and abandon the Applicable Project for such CoTenant, and its Undivided Interest is not accepted by the other CoTenant(s) or the obligations under this Agreement of the surrendering CoTenant are not assumed by the other CoTenant(s) in writing, the withdrawing CoTenant shall, upon notice to the other CoTenant(s) of the intent to abandon such Applicable Project, (x) except as may be otherwise agreed in writing with the other CoTenant(s), at its sole cost and expense, remove any Project Specific Assets of the Applicable Project Company of the Withdrawing CoTenant, and (y) be responsible for (i) its Undivided Interest of the costs and expenses of the removal and wind-up of the Shared Facilities, (ii) all costs and expenses of the removal and wind-up of any such Project Specific Assets from the Shared Premises, and (iii) a lump sum amount representing the net present value increase, if any, to the Shared Expenses over the remaining useful life of the Shared Assets as a result of permanent improvements or alterations to the Shared Facilities that are not removed pursuant to Section 6.14.1(x) (including any Additional Shared Facilities) required by such withdrawing CoTenant pursuant to Section 3.6 or otherwise installed by such withdrawing CoTenant, to the extent such improvements or alterations, or Additional Shared Facilities were for the benefit of the withdrawing CoTenant (collectively, the Withdrawal Costs). The surrendering CoTenant shall, within thirty (30) days of the receipt of a written notice of the Manager of the Withdrawal Costs, pay the Withdrawal Costs to the Manager and shall be solely responsible for payment of any of its liabilities to third parties relating to such Applicable Project and the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities, including an obligation to indemnify remaining Co-Tenants for and against any liabilities to third parties attributable to the withdrawing Co-Tenant for the period prior to the Withdrawal Date but as to which the remaining Co-Tenants may be held jointly and severally liable. The Withdrawal Costs shall be maintained by the Manager in a reserve account and used by the Manager for removal of the Shared Facilities and the restoration of the Shared Premises when same becomes necessary. 6.14.2 Upon and subject to the terms, conditions, restrictions and reservations set forth in this Agreement, and subject to obtaining any Governmental Approvals required by applicable Law, effective upon the Withdrawal Date, the withdrawing CoTenant shall, without additional compensation, be deemed to have Transferred to the other CoTenant(s) its Undivided Interest in and to the Shared Facilities, AS IS, WITH ALL FAULTS AND WITHOUT ANY REPRESENTATIONS OR WARRANTIES WHATSOEVER, EITHER EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, AND SPECIFICALLY EXCLUDING ANY WARRANTY OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, OR ANY OTHER WARRANTY ARISING UNDER STATUTORY OR COMMON LAW. The intent of the foregoing is that the remaining CoTenant(s) shall own all undivided interests in the Shared Facilities. Notwithstanding the foregoing, no such Transfer or withdrawal shall relieve the withdrawing CoTenant of any Liability that it has incurred prior to the Withdrawal Date or that arise with respect to periods prior to the Withdrawal Date under provisions of this Agreement that survive termination of this Agreement or that accrue against the Shared Facilities, Shared Premises, other CoTenant(s), or Manager as a result of such withdrawal. 6.14.3 Release of Rights to Shared Facilities. Effective upon the Withdrawal Date, subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, and subject to obtaining any Governmental Approvals required by applicable Law, the withdrawing CoTenant shall, without compensation, either release, assign or terminate, as applicable, its rights in the Shared Facilities, as may be requested by the remaining CoTenant(s) in writing; provided, however, that such release, assignment or termination shall not materially and adversely affect any remaining Applicable Project, the Shared Facilities or the Shared Premises. 6.15 Remaining Obligations . After its Withdrawal Date, the withdrawing CoTenant shall remain a party to this Agreement but shall have no rights or obligations under this Agreement except those set forth in Section 4.1, Section 4.2, and Section 4.3 (in each case, relating to the payment of its Undivided Interest (prior to the Withdrawal Date) of (a) Shared Expenses incurred prior to the Withdrawal Date, (b) Removal Costs, as reasonably projected by the Manager), Section 5.4, Article 11 and Article 13, and (c) any indemnification or reimbursement obligations, including third party liabilities, that arise from facts occurring prior to the Withdrawal Date, including those that result in claims following the Withdrawal Date). 6.15.1 Responsibility for Costs and Expenses. All reasonable costs and expenses, including reasonable attorneys fees and expenses, incurred by the Manager or remaining CoTenant(s) or any of their respective Applicable Project Companies in connection with the actual or proposed withdrawal of a CoTenant shall be paid or reimbursed by the withdrawing CoTenant upon any request therefor from the Manager and the remaining CoTenant(s), as applicable. 6.16 Admission of New CoTenants . (a) For cause. Provided that a replacement Manager has been selected by the CoTenants (excluding the CoTenant that is then acting as the Manager), the Manager may be removed by the vote of a majority of the CoTenants, acting reasonably and excluding the CoTenant that is then acting as the Manager, if Manager (i) breaches any material provision of this Agreement or the CoTenancy Agreement or fails to meet the Standard of Performance and fails to cure any such breach, action or omission within thirty (30) days after receiving notice thereof from any CoTenant (or, if such cure cannot reasonably be completed within such thirty (30) day period, Manager fails to undertake and promptly cure upon receipt of such notice or fails to give adequate assurances to the CoTenants that such breach or action will be so cured with all reasonable speed, not to exceed another thirty (30) days), (ii) engages in gross negligence or willful misconduct in the performance of its obligations hereunder or under the CoTenancy Agreement, (iii) dissolves, liquidates or terminates its corporate or limited liability company existence, or (iv) is a CoTenant and such CoTenant sells, assigns, or otherwise transfers its rights or interests in the Shared Assets or this Agreement. During such times, if any, as: (1) the circumstances described in clause (i) or (ii) above exist, and (2) an Event of Default hereunder is ongoing with respect to a CoTenant affiliated with the Manager, the non-defaulting CoTenants may unilaterally remove the Manager. Any CoTenant seeking to remove the Manager pursuant to this Section 7.4(a) shall provide notice to the other CoTenants of such removal at the same time as notice is given to the Manager. Provided that a replacement Manager has been selected by the Required Parties, the Manager may be removed without cause upon the written consent of the Required Parties. 7.5 Resignation of the Manager . The Manager may resign from its position as Manager if any of the following occur: (a) any CoTenants failure to make undisputed payments to Manager when such payments are due and payable under this Agreement, unless within sixty (60) days after written notice from Manager to the CoTenants of such non-payment, all such undisputed payments are made to Manager in accordance herewith; (b) all of the CoTenants dissolve, liquidate, withdraw, or terminate their corporate existence; or (c) the Manager provides ninety (90) days written notice to each CoTenant of its intention to resign as Manager hereunder (in which case the CoTenants shall promptly appoint a successor Manager within such ninety (90) day period). In any scenario described in this Section 7.5, the Manager shall, in good faith, continue to perform its duties and obligations as the Manager until such time as a successor Manager is appointed hereunder. 7.6 Obligations at End of Term or Upon Removal or Resignation . The Manager shall perform all services with respect to the Shared Facilities and the Shared Premises as required under this Agreement through the date of termination or expiration of this Agreement or the removal or resignation of the Manager in accordance with this Article 7, and each CoTenant shall make all payments required by it hereunder through such date, with all such payments to be made in full within thirty (30) days after such termination, expiration, removal or resignation. No removal or resignation of the Manager in accordance with this Article 7 shall be effective unless and until a successor Manager is appointed with the written approval of each CoTenant. In the event of any removal or resignation of the Manager in accordance with this Article 7, the Manager shall provide reasonable assistance to the CoTenants to assure a smooth, efficient transition of its services to a replacement Manager including providing any required notice to a Governmental Authority, for which Manager shall be reimbursed its reasonable expenses in connection therewith. 7.7 Successor Manager . Any successor Manager must be or must become a Party to this Agreement by executing and delivering a Joinder Agreement in the form attached hereto as Exhibit I (or such other form as is reasonably acceptable to the other Parties). Any successor Manager hereunder shall be appointed by written consent of the Required Parties; provided, however, that if the Manager is removed pursuant to Section 7.4(a)(i) or (ii) and the Manager is also a CoTenant, approval of such CoTenant shall not be required (and such CoTenants Percentage Interest shall be excluded from determining the Required Parties) if the successor Manager meets the Minimum Experience Requirements. Each CoTenant represents, as of the Effective Date that it has reviewed the terms of such documents and information that it has deemed appropriate, and that it has made its own appraisal in respect of the Shared Facilities independently and without reliance on the Manager. Each CoTenant shall review the terms of such other documents and information that at the time it may deem appropriate, and it shall continue to make its own appraisal in respect of the Shared Facilities or in respect of any other matter for which such CoTenant may be entitled to vote or give consent under this Agreement, in any such case, independently and without reliance on the Manager. 8. DUTIES OF THE MANAGER 8.1 In General . The CoTenants hereby direct the Manager to at all times do the following: (a) cause the Shared Assets to be operated, maintained and repaired pursuant to Prudent Industry Practices, and any applicable Laws; (b) take any and all action as may be reasonably necessary to enforce and preserve warranty claims or other claims related to the Shared Assets; (c) oversee all investigations, audits, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any Governmental Authority applicable to the CoTenants use, operation or ownership of the Shared Assets, and keep the CoTenants fully apprised as to the foregoing matters affecting the Shared Assets; (d) act as the master owner and single point of contact for communications between (i) the CoTenants, (ii) the CoTenants and the landowners of the Shared Premises and (iii) any relevant Governmental Authority, in each case, as related to the Shared Assets (including curtailment orders affecting the Projects); (e) perform all regulatory reporting, auditing and other related matters (including with respect to any obligations imposed by NERC or FERC on the Shared Assets) arising out of, or in connection with, the Shared Assets; (f) intentionally omitted; (g) maintain all books and records relating to the Shared Assets as may be required by Law or requested by the CoTenants; (h) submit to all Governmental Authorities any required reports or filings relating to the Shared Assets; (i) perform all duties, responsibilities and obligations of the Manager under and as set forth in the CoTenancy Agreement; and (j) take such other actions as are reasonably necessary to effectuate the foregoing, unless in any such case, such action is not in the commercially reasonable interest of the CoTenants. 8.2 Specific Authority . Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, the Manager may take any of the following actions without further approval from the CoTenants: 8.2.1 conduct day-to-day management, operations and maintenance of the Shared Assets; 8.2.2 negotiate, enter into, execute, acknowledge or amend subcontract for the management, use, operation, maintenance, and repair of the Shared Assets, in each case in accordance with the then-effective Annual Shared Facilities Budget or if not within the then-effective Annual Shared Facilities Budget, so long as the amount incurred with respect to such subcontract, determined in the aggregate with any such other agreement, is less than ten percent (10%) of the aggregate amount under the then-effective Annual Shared Facilities Budget; provided, however, that (a) no such actions shall materially and adversely affect the rights or privileges of any of the CoTenants under this Agreement or their use, operation, access to or availability of the Shared Assets, (b) the Manager shall provide each CoTenant with copies of any such subcontract promptly upon execution thereof, and (c) each such subcontract must comply with the Standard of Performance; 8.2.3 pay and collect amounts due in connection with the Shared Assets, and maintain one or more bank accounts in the name of the CoTenants wherein funds received by the Manager in connection with its duties hereunder shall be maintained, in each case in accordance with the then-effective Annual Shared Facilities Budget; 8.2.4 procure insurance policies pursuant to Article 12; or 8.2.5 execute, acknowledge, and deliver any and all instruments and take such other steps as are reasonably necessary to effectuate the foregoing and as are consistent therewith. 8.3 Limitation on Authority . 8.3.1 The Manager shall not, without the written approval of the Required Parties: (a) create or cause to be created any Lien on any of the Shared Assets, or any Lien on any Applicable Project, any Project Specific Assets, or any CoTenants Undivided Interest; (b) take any action that would prevent the development, construction or operation of, otherwise result in an impairment of, a CoTenants Applicable Project or Project Specific Assets or the Shared Assets, unless required to do so by applicable Law; (c) perform or omit to perform any act that would cause any Person reasonably to believe that the Manager is a partner of the CoTenants or authorized to bind such CoTenants, except as expressly authorized herein; (d) Transfer all or any portion of the Undivided Interests held by any CoTenant, or any components of the Shared Facilities (other than pursuant to this Agreement); (e) borrow funds or otherwise incur indebtedness on behalf of a CoTenant, or cause a CoTenant to act as a surety, grant guarantees or incur similar liabilities on behalf of third parties, directly or indirectly, whether for borrowed money or otherwise; (f) amend, modify, change, waive, or grant forbearance of any term of this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement, the CoTenancy Agreement or any Shared Premises Agreement; (g) procure any insurance coverage that is less than the coverages required by this Agreement; (h) change the capacity characteristics of the Shared Facilities; (i) incur an expense of more than Twenty-Five Thousand Dollars ($25,000) in any instance or cumulative expenses of more than Two Hundred Fifty Thousand Dollars ($250,000) in any calendar year that is not included in the Annual Shared Facilities Budget or required to address an Emergency; (j) compromise or settle any claims; or (k) take any action that would cause any CoTenant or Applicable Project Company to become subject to, or not exempt from, regulation as a public utility by the State PRC. 8.4 Reporting; Notices; Records . The Manager shall: (a) to the extent requested by a CoTenant and in the Managers possession or reasonably available to the Manager, provide data and information regarding the Shared Assets performance and availability; (b) promptly provide to the CoTenants written notice of any communications, orders or requirements of any Governmental Authority affecting the Shared Assets, in each case received by the Manager or of which the Manager has received written notice; (c) except to the extent otherwise provided to the CoTenant pursuant to the CoTenancy Agreement, provide to the applicable CoTenant written notice of any communications, orders or requirements of any Governmental Authority or Transmission Provider affecting the CoTenants Applicable Project, in each case received by the Manager or of which the Manager has received written notice, including communications that are addressed to a CoTenant or that are sent to the Manager instead of the CoTenant by mistake of the Governmental Authority or Transmission Provider; (d) to the extent requested by a CoTenant and in the Managers possession or reasonably available to the Manager, provide any information regarding the Shared Assets required for any reports to, or filings with, any Governmental Authority; (e) report promptly (and in any event within twenty-four (24) hours of becoming aware thereof) to the CoTenants and to any other Persons entitled to receive such notice any incident of Force Majeure or Emergency on the Shared Premises or otherwise adversely affecting any of the Shared Assets, of which Manager becomes aware; and (f) provide such other reports and information as may be reasonably requested by the CoTenants under the terms of this Agreement. 8.5 Audit Rights . The Manager shall allow the CoTenants and the CoTenants authorized Representatives to inspect and audit the books and records maintained by the Manager with respect to the Shared Assets (at the CoTenants sole cost and expense); provided, however, that each of the CoTenants shall, at its own expense, only have the right to inspect and audit such books and records for any period that is within two (2) calendar years from the date an applicable payment is made hereunder or the final settlement or disposition of any claim is made pursuant to this Agreement. On or before November 1st of each year, the Manager shall provide each CoTenant with a draft of the annual budget (an Annual Shared Facilities Budget) related to the operation, maintenance and repair of the Shared Assets and describing the scheduled work to be completed in the following calendar year and the general operational plans for the Shared Assets during such year, including responsibilities and emergency procedures and detailing the expected revenue and expenses for the following calendar year including explanations for any material differences from the prior calendar year. Such draft budget shall include, at a minimum, the billing rates, estimated cost, based on time and materials, and all fees and reimbursable costs contemplated in this Agreement, for anticipated operation and maintenance services and repairs to be provided by or contracted for by the Manager during each month of the following year (or portions thereof), including any other expected Shared Expenses. Each CoTenant may submit any comments or questions to the Manager within thirty (30) days of receipt of the draft Annual Shared Facilities Budget. The Manager shall incorporate any comments received, as appropriate, and shall provide a final Annual Shared Facilities Budget to the CoTenants by December 15th of each year for approval by the Required Parties. If the Required Parties are unable to reach an agreement with respect to the final Annual Shared Facilities Budget prior to the beginning of the calendar year, the Annual Shared Facilities Budget for the previous calendar year, increased per year by inflation factor for such year as computed and published by the U.S. Department of Commerce. The Annual Shared Facilities Budget may be amended during the year with the written consent of the Required Parties. 8.7 Emergencies . Upon the occurrence of a Loss Event, the Manager or any CoTenant receiving notice shall provide the other Parties with reasonable advance written notice of any impending proceeding or meeting related to such Loss Event and shall not in the absence of the written consent of the Required Parties settle with any Governmental Authority in respect thereof or agree on compensation for such Loss Event. The Manager shall, as soon as reasonably practicable, prepare a written proposal (a Restoration Proposal) in consultation with the CoTenants to rebuild, repair, restore or replace the portion of the Shared Assets affected by such Loss Event, which Restoration Proposal shall contain, in appropriate detail, (a) a budget identifying all categories and approximate amounts reasonably anticipated to be incurred, (b) a progress and completion schedule and (c) a written plan, in each case, for the proposed rebuilding, repair, restoration or replacement of the Shared Assets. The Manager, to the extent necessary or prudent, may coordinate preparation of the Restoration Proposal with similar activity undertaken by or on behalf of any of the CoTenants arising out of the Loss Event in respect of Project Specific Assets. Within thirty (30) days after receipt of a Restoration Proposal from the Manager, each CoTenant shall notify the Manager and each other CoTenant in writing of whether it elects to participate in the rebuilding, repair, restoration or replacement of the Shared Assets. Any costs, expenses or other Liabilities associated with the rebuilding, repair, restoration or replacement of the portion of the Shared Assets affected by a Loss Event shall be Shared Expenses reimbursed by each CoTenant that has elected to participate in such activity, in proportion to its Percentage Interest with respect to losses associated with the Shared Premises and in proportion to its Undivided Interests with respect to losses associated with the Shared Facilities, or each applicable Segment thereof.
